class Solution {
    public int findChampion(int n, int[][] edges) {
        int[] degree = new int[n];
        for (int[] e : edges) {
            degree[e[1]]++;
        }
        int champion = -1;
        for (int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if (degree[i] == 0) {
                if (champion == -1) {
                    champion = i;
                } else {
                    return -1;
                }
            }
        }
        return champion;
    }
}

Explanation:
In this code, we first create an array 'degree' of length n which will keep track of the number of nodes that are directed towards each node (i.e., the number of nodes that the node has an edge directed towards it). For each edge in the input, we increment the count for the second node in the edge, since the second node is directed towards the first.

Then we traverse the 'degree' array. If any node has degree 0, that means it does not have any nodes that are directed towards it. If we have seen a champion before and now we see another team with degree 0, it means that there are multiple teams that don't have any teams stronger than themselves, and we return -1. If we have not seen a champion yet, this team is the champion and we store its index in 'champion'.

Finally, if there exists a champion, we return the index of the champion. If not, we return -1. 

Time complexity: O(n+m), where n is the number of nodes and m is the number of edges in the graph. We need to traverse all nodes and all edges once.
Space complexity: O(n), where n is the number of nodes in the graph. We need to store the in-degree of all nodes.

